Hello Fred,

It turns out HyperNEAT does not tend to produce modular neural=
 networks by default. See: 

Clune J, Beckmann BE, McKinley PK, and Ofria C=
 (2010) Investigating whether HyperNEAT produces modular neural networks. P=
roceedings of the Genetic and Evolutionary Computation Conference. 635-642.=
 http://jeffclune.com/publications/Clune-ModularityInHyperNEAT-Gecco2010.pd=
f

But it can be modified to do so, in two different ways, as described in =
these papers:
Huizinga J, Mouret JB, Clune J (2014) Evolving Neural Network=
s That Are Both Modular and Regular: HyperNeat Plus the Connection Cost Tec=
hnique. Proceedings of the Genetic and Evolutionary Computation Conference.=
 (pdf) (video)
P. Verbancsics and K.O. Stanley. Constraining connectivity t=
o encourage modularity in hyperneat. In Proceedings of the 13th annual conf=
erence on Genetic and evolutionary computation, pages 1483=961490. ACM, 201=
1.


Best regards,
Jeff Clune

Assistant Professor
Computer Science
Univers=
ity of Wyoming
jeffclune@...
jeffclune.com

On Sep 10, 2014, at 9:45 A=
M, lordalveric@... [neat] <neat@yahoogroups.com> wrote:

> 
> It just=
 occurred to me that HyperNEAT is an example of modular neural composition =
that can be generalized to any arbitrary modular neural composition. The co=
mposition of TWEANNS would be, of course evaluated and evolved as a unit.
>=
 
> 
> 
> Have anyone tried this approach at all beyond HyperNEAT? 
> 
> 
>=
 
> -Fred Mitchell
> 
> 
> 


--Apple-Mail=_A11FA907-40A7-479B-A27E-0E675AB88822
